, and Ingrained Barriers in a Transborder Region -- tNAFTA and Transportation Corridor Improvement in WesternNorth America: Restructuring for the Twenty-First Century -- tBorders as Metaphors -- tPermeable Borders and Boundaries in a Globalizing World: Feeling at Home amidst Global Poverty -- tTechnopoles and Development in a “Borderless”World: Boundaries Erased, Boundaries Constructed -- tRethinking Borders – Lines, Spaces, and Continua -- tComplex Emergency Response Planning and Coordination: Potential GIS Applications -- tGood Neighbour Diplomacy Revisited -- tConclusions -- tTowards a Geopolitics of Life and Living: Where Boundaries Still Matter -- tFrom the International to the Local in the Study and Representation of Boundaries: Theoretical and Methodological Comments -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe era of globalization has produced significant changes in the borderland issues of trade, security, economics, health, and even the environment. While borders may seem more permeable than they once were, can it really be said that we live in a "borderless world"? Holding the Line considers the changing roles of modern borders, contending that they not only remain relevant but also have become increasingly important as a site for negotiating the competing demands of globalization and national sovereignty. Exploring contemporary borders from a broad range of perspectives -- legal, environmental, sociological, economic, geopolitical, and historical -- and using examples from various regions in Europe, North America, Southeast Asia, and Latin America, the contributors use a holistic approach to understand the impact of boundaries on both society and space. They demonstrate that any attempt to create a methodological and conceptual framework for the understanding of boundaries must be concerned with the process of bounding, rather than simply the means through which physical lines of separation are delimited and demarcated. Borders, they conclude, are as much metaphors as they are realities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBoundaries. 0aFrontières. 0aFrontières. 0aGlobalization. 0aInternational relations. 0aMondialisation. 0aRelations internationales. 0aSouveraineté. 0aSouveraineté. 0aSovereignty. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aAdamson, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlper, Donald K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArtibise, Alan F.J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAsiwaju, Anthony I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlake, Gerald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBort, Eberhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradbury, Susan L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBradshaw, Roy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrunn, Stanley D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohn, Theodore H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColeman, Mathew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Thomas M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFargo, Timothy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGault, Ian Townsend, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenrikson, Alan K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIII, Daniel E. Turbeville, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca